Acquisition of Gesture

Dan Yurovsky

2017-06-22

Lets try out some basic descriptives. What do these things look like? Lets arrange them in order of difficulty(on the bases of highest proportion of non-producers).

eng_data <- get_instrument_data(instrument_language = "English", 
                                instrument_form = "WG",
                                administrations = TRUE,
                                iteminfo = TRUE)

gesture_data <- eng_data %>%
  filter(str_detect(type, "gesture"))

# Get the First Gestures
first_gestures <- gesture_data %>% 
  filter(type == "gestures_first") %>%
  filter(!is.na(value)) %>%
  mutate(value = parse_factor(value, c("not yet", "sometimes", "often"))) %>%
  group_by(age, definition, value) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>%
  mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>%
  complete(age, definition, value, fill = list(n = 0)) 

# Order by approxiamate acquistion order to make plotting nicer
acq_order <- first_gestures %>%
  filter(value == "not yet") %>%
  group_by(definition) %>%
  summarise(n = mean(n)) %>%
  arrange(n)

first_gestures_ordered <- first_gestures %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(definition = parse_factor(definition, acq_order$definition))

ggplot(first_gestures_ordered, aes(x = age, y = n, color = value, label = value)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ definition) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE) +
  geom_dl(method = list(dl.trans(x=x +.2), "last.qp", cex=1)) +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1") + 
  scale_x_continuous(name = "age (months)", limits = c(7.5, 21),
                    breaks = seq(8, 18))

I cant tell if sometimes/often really carries very much signal. It looks like its all over the place for the earliest gestures and almost overlapping for the latest ones. Lets try compressing to a binary

first_gestures_binary <- first_gestures_ordered %>%
  filter(value == "not yet") %>%
  mutate(known = 1- n)

ggplot(first_gestures_binary, aes(x = age, y = known, color = definition, 
                                  label = definition)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE) +
  geom_dl(method = list(dl.trans(x=x -.2), "first.qp", cex=1)) +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1") + 
  scale_x_continuous(name = "age (months)", limits = c(5.5, 18.5),
                    breaks = seq(8, 18))

These look pretty reasonable to me, and a lot more stable. Also smacklip doesnt seem to have much of any kind of trajectory, which makes me think that parents dont know what do with it. For comparison, lets try the other gesture categories.

# Get the First Gestures
other <- gesture_data %>% 
  filter(type != "gestures_first") %>%
  filter(!is.na(value)) %>%
  mutate(value = parse_factor(value, c("no", "yes"))) %>%
  group_by(age, type, definition, value) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>%
  mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>%
  complete(age, nesting(type, definition), value, fill = list(n = 0)) %>%
  filter(value == "yes")

# Order by approxiamate acquistion order to make plotting nicer
other_type_order <- other %>%
  group_by(type, definition) %>%
  summarise(n = mean(n)) %>%
  summarise(n = mean(n)) %>%
  arrange(desc(n))

other_indiv_order <- other %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(type = parse_factor(type, other_type_order$type)) %>%
  group_by(type, definition) %>%
  summarise(n = mean(n)) %>%
  arrange(desc(n)) 

other_gestures_ordered <- other %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(type = parse_factor(type, other_type_order$type)) %>%
  mutate(definition = parse_factor(definition, other_indiv_order$definition))

ggplot(other_gestures_ordered, aes(x = age, y = n, color = definition, 
                                  label = definition)) +
  facet_wrap(~ type) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE) +
  geom_dl(method = list(dl.trans(x=x -.2), "first.qp", cex=1)) +
  #scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1") + 
  scale_x_continuous(name = "age (months)", limits = c(5.5, 18.5),
                    breaks = seq(8, 18))

Interesting, ok most of these look like they have some signal (with the exception maybe of sobig). Also some of them dont look terribly different from the First Gestures.

Lets try looking at correlations with vocabulary size

cor_data <- gesture_data %>%
  filter(!is.na(value), !value %in% c("no", "not yet")) %>%
  group_by(age, comprehension, production, data_id) %>%
  summarise(produced_gestures = n())

cols <- c("comprehension", "production", "produced_gestures")

cor_data %>% select_(.dots = cols) %>%
  ggcorplot()

Wow, age is really predictive of gesture, even more so than comprehension/production. Lets looking at the effect when we fit age simultaneously.

num_gestures <- length(unique(gesture_data$definition))

age_cor <- glmer(cbind(produced_gestures, num_gestures - produced_gestures) 
                 ~ scale(age) + (1|data_id), 
                 family = "binomial", data = cor_data)


age_production_cor <- glmer(cbind(produced_gestures, num_gestures - produced_gestures) 
                 ~ scale(age) + scale(production) + (1|data_id), 
                 family = "binomial", data = cor_data)

Ok so all of the things that are positively correlated contain some signal in predicting each-other over and above age. It also looks like there is some non-linearity in the correlation, because the age * comprehension/production correlations are negative. Presumably this is some kind of ceiling effect where the gestures in general are producted before the words? Lets check that next.
